<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-478-928  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 478 928.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 31 1989 v6 n30 p66(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Easy electronic signatures. (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Creative Software Solutions Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Signature on a Disk (Computer program) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSoftware packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The story goes that when Creative Software Solutions Inc. Chairman Ed Reisigattended Comdex/Fall in Las Vegas last year, he noticed that several vendorsexhibiting equipment worth thousands of dollars were being asked to signletters and checks.andM;So, Reisig set out to provide a cost-effective way to reproduce signaturesusing a personal computer, a standard printer and custom software.andM;The custom software is here: It's called Signature on a Disk.andM;For $129, it stores two signatures, digitized by Creative Software at itsheadquarters in Fort Worth, Texas.andM;Signature on a Disk is designed for people who sign more than 50 checks aweek.andM;Security is so good that users must call the company to find out how to getthe demo disk started.andP;  After that, security is the user's responsibility.andM;For corporate PC professionals, technical expertise is no longer enough.andO;Increasingly, micro managers must understand the business functions that makea company tick.andP;  Each week, this digest will examine a corporate function orindustry, its data requirements and the PC applications that meet thoseneeds.andP;  The premise: The better PC professionals understand users' businessgoals, the more valuable corporate resources they and their PCs become.andP;  Nextweek's digest examines the use of PCs in health care.andM;-- Compiled by Paul E. Schindler Jr.andO;</TEXT></DOC>